body: The first error is just a syntax error from not having a comma after `validation_batch_size=10,`. Not sure what's going on with the second error. I assume you mean this is happening with `model.fit` in both cases? Which version of tensorflow are you using? As @eduramiba pointed out 2.0 is still a bit buggy. The code seems to be most stable with tensorflow 1.14 (`pip install tensorflow~=1.14` or `pip install tensorflow-gpu~=1.14`). Also is tensorflow printing out anything in your jupyter notebook terminal session? Could you also post a screenshot of your nvidia-smi? (In terminal, run the command: `watch -n 0.1 nvidia-smi`)

I added the code from edurambia before the "create a trainingGenerator" line and I still have the problem, even after restarting from the beginning and unchanged data from Jake.
Yes, it is happening in both cases with model.fit. I"m using tensorflow version 1.14.0
![jupyter terminal sesson](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/55141900/66558300-a08e3d00-eb53-11e9-8df3-83916bec1bc1.png)

It seems you don't have the proper drivers + cuda 10.0 installation to show `nvidia-smi`.

This is my usual script to do it in ubuntu 18.04:

```bash
# Nvidia drivers
sudo apt install build-essential dkms gcc-multilib
wget http://es.download.nvidia.com/XFree86/Linux-x86_64/430.50/NVIDIA-Linux-x86_64-430.50.run
sudo chmod +x NVIDIA-Linux-x86_64-430.50.run
sudo ./NVIDIA-Linux-x86_64-430.50.run --dkms -s --no-cc-version-check
rm NVIDIA-Linux-x86_64-430.14.run

# Install CUDA 10.0 (until tensorflow supports 10.1)

wget https://developer.nvidia.com/compute/cuda/10.0/Prod/local_installers/cuda_10.0.130_410.48_linux
sudo sh cuda_10.0.130_410.48_linux --silent
wget http://developer.download.nvidia.com/compute/cuda/10.0/Prod/patches/1/cuda_10.0.130.1_linux.run
sudo sh cuda_10.0.130.1_linux.run --silent
rm cuda_*

# Install CUDNN
#download cudnn-10.0-linux-x64-v7.6.4.38.tgz manually, you need to login: https://developer.nvidia.com/cudnn
tar -xzvf cudnn-10.0-linux-x64-v7.6.4.38.tgz
sudo cp cuda/include/cudnn.h /usr/local/cuda-10.0/include
sudo cp cuda/lib64/libcudnn* /usr/local/cuda-10.0/lib64
sudo chmod a+r /usr/local/cuda-10.0/include/cudnn.h /usr/local/cuda-10.0/lib64/libcudnn*
sudo rm -r cuda
rm cudnn*

# Conda python
wget https://repo.anaconda.com/miniconda/Miniconda2-latest-Linux-x86_64.sh
sh Miniconda2-latest-Linux-x86_64.sh
rm Miniconda2-latest-Linux-x86_64.sh

echo 'export PATH="/home/youruser/miniconda2/bin:$PATH"' >> /home/youruser/bashrc
echo 'export LD_LIBRARY_PATH="$LD_LIBRARY_PATH:/usr/local/cuda-10.0/lib64:/usr/local/cuda-10.0/extras/CUPTI/lib64"' >> /home/youruser/.zshrc

# Create tensorflow env
conda create --name tensorflow python=3.7
source activate tensorflow
pip install tensorflow-gpu
```

The error appears to be some internal Tensorflow issue with using the CPU, which I can't help you with. @eduramiba's script should work to install the GPU version of Tensorflow with Anaconda if you have a Nvidia GPU. Also check the official Tensorflow installation guide: https://www.tensorflow.org/install/gpu

`(base)` suggests you're already inside the conda base environment. I don't think you can activate another environment if you're already in one.
Try:
```bash
conda deactivate
conda activate tensorflow
```
Or:
```bash
source ~/.profile
conda activate tensorflow
```

Make sure to download cudnn manually as the script says. This is the script I used for my Ubuntu workstation (just replace the last part with installation with anaconda): https://gist.github.com/Mahedi-61/2a2f1579d4271717d421065168ce6a73
